'''Solomon Ngobeni''' (died 14 November 1989) was the last person to be [[Capital punishment|executed]] by the government of [[South Africa]].

In October 1987, Ngobeni shot and robbed [[taxicab|taxi]] driver Mackson Kubayi in [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]]. Ngobeni was convicted of murder and was [[hanging|hanged]] at [[Pretoria Central Prison]] on 14 November 1989.

In 1990, [[President of South Africa|President]] [[F. W. de Klerk]] declared a [[moratorium (law)|moratorium]] on the execution of capital sentences. In June 1995, in the case of ''[[S v Makwanyane]]'', the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]] held that capital punishment was an [[unconstitutional]] form of punishment.

